The correct logic for determining exponent for scientific notation: we want to find how many trailing zeros the integer has. A better approach: count trailing zeros by repeatedly dividing by 10 while remainder is 0. Then if the number of trailing zeros is > 2, output in scientific notation: (value / 10^exp) + "E" + exp. But the buggy function uses a while loop that incorrectly uses multiplication. A minimal fix could be:

```java
void addNumber(double x) {
    char prev = getLastChar();
    if (x < 0 && prev == '-') {
        add(" ");
    }

    if ((long) x == x) {
        long value = (long) x;
        long mantissa = value;
        int exp = 0;
        if (Math.abs(x) >= 100) {
            // Count trailing zeros
            while (mantissa % 10 == 0 && mantissa != 0) {
                mantissa /= 10;
                exp++;
            }
        }
        if (exp > 2) {
            add(Long.toString(mantissa) + "E" + Integer.toString(exp));
        } else {
            add(Long.toString(value));
        }
    } else {
        add(String.valueOf(x));
    }
}
```

That is a minimal fix: replace the problematic while condition with a simple trailing zero count.

